-- PRESS DIGEST - Bulgaria - Sept 15
-- 
-- Mon Sep 15, 2014 03:02AM EDT
-- None



SOFIA, Sept 15 (Reuters) - These are some of the main stories in Bulgarian newspapers on Monday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

-- Some 1,000 people have been defined as potentially involved in vote buying at the upcoming early parliamentary elections, the interior ministry said (Capital daily, Presa, Monitor, Sega, Duma).  -- Right-wing coalition Reformist Bloc, a group of five parties, launched its parliamentary election campaign on Sunday without holding a leadership election after plans to do so were brought down by internal squabbling (Capital daily, Presa, Monitor, 24 Chasa, Sega, Duma). -- The environment ministry warned of new torrential rains in the beginning of this week. Rising of water levels in the rivers is also to be expected (Standart, Presa, Monitor, Duma).  -- Some 64,000 Bulgarian children are going to school for the first time on Sept. 15, the education ministry said. However, the new school year will start with unfinished repairs in over 50 schools throughout the Balkan country (Monitor, Sega, Duma). MERIDIAN MATCH - Players from soccer club Levski Sofia have threatened to boycott training sessions over unpaid wages. There was no immediate official response from the club to the ultimatum.